Claims 1. A surgical device for removal of biological specimens from within a patient, the device comprising: a retrieval bag having an open end, a closed end, and at least one wall extending between the open end and the closed end; one or more memory wires configured for coupling to the retrieval bag wherein the memory wire is configured to collapse into a first compressed shape when receiving a compressive force, and expand into a second resting shape when the compressive force is released; wherein responsive to the one or more memory wires expanding, the retrieval bag expands; and wherein responsive to the one or more memory wires collapsing, the retrieval bag collapses. 2. The surgical device of claim 1, wherein the open end includes a channel around the circumference to receive a string or cord with a first free end and a second free end configured to cinch or close the retrieval bag upon application of a pull or tensile force. 3. The surgical device of any preceding claim, further including one or more tunnels coupled to the retrieval bag, the tunnel being configured to receive the memory wire; and wherein the one or more memory wires are configured to enter or exit the one or more tunnels. 4. The surgical device of claim 3, wherein the one or more memory wires have a smaller diameter distal end and a larger diameter proximal end; wherein the smaller diameter distal end is positioned closer to the retrieval bag's closed end and the larger diameter is positioned closer to the retrieval bag's open end. 5. The surgical device of any preceding claim wherein the one or more memory wires are positioned on a sidewall of the retrieval bag between the open end and the closed end. 6. The surgical device of any preceding claim wherein the one or more memory wires travels longitudinally and radially around a sidewall of the retrieval bag between the open end and the closed end. 7. The surgical device of any preceding claim wherein a first memory wire travels longitudinally and clockwise radially around a sidewall of the retrieval bag between the open end and the closed end; and a second memory wire travels longitudinally and counter-clockwise radially around a sidewall of the retrieval bag between the open end and the closed end. 8. The surgical device of claim 7 wherein the first memory wire and the second memory wire cross between the open end and the closed end. 9. The surgical device of any preceding claim further including: an introducer comprised of a longitudinally extending first lumen with a first proximal end and a first distal end with a first diameter; and a movable actuator comprised of a longitudinal body having a second diameter smaller than the first diameter, a second proximal end and a second distal end; wherein the actuator is positioned within the introducer and movable longitudinally through the lumen of the introducer; wherein the retrieval bag is positioned in a first compressed position within the lumen of the introducer and distal to the distal end of the actuator; wherein upon application of a first push or compressive force upon the actuator from the actuator's second proximal end and towards the actuator's second distal end, the retrieval bag is moved from the first compressed position within the lumen of the introducer to a second deployed position outside of the introducer. 10. The surgical device of claim 9, wherein when the one or more memory wires are coupled to the retrieval bag in a first compressed position within the lumen of the introducer and released simultaneously with the retrieval bag in the second position when deployed outside of the introducer. 11. The surgical device of claim 9, wherein the one or more memory wires are positioned proximal to the retrieval bag in the first compressed position and deployed after the retrieval bag. 12. The surgical device of claim 9, 10 and 11, wherein upon application of an retractive pull or tensile force to the actuator, the actuator is withdrawn from the introducer's first distal end towards the introducer's first proximal end. 13. The surgical device of claim 12, wherein the one or more memory wires remain coupled to the retrieval bag. 14. The surgical device of claim 12, wherein the one or more memory wires are withdrawn or decoupled from the retrieval bag and retracts with the actuator. 15. The surgical device of claim 12, 13 and 14, wherein the retrieval bag is decoupled from the actuator. 16. The surgical device of claims 3-16, wherein the one or more tunnels are configured for receiving fluid. 17. The surgical device of claim 9-15, wherein the actuator's longitudinal body is a lumen with a hollow inner channel. 18. The surgical device of claim 17, wherein the one or more tunnels are configured for receiving fluid; and wherein the tunnels are in fluid communication with the actuator and the actuator has a fluid intake port at the proximal end. 19. The surgical device of claims 18, wherein upon application of a push or compressive force to the actuator, the actuator delivers fluid into the one or more tunnels. 20. The surgical device of claims 18-19, wherein upon application of a retractive pull or tensile force to the actuator, the actuator withdraws fluid from the one or more tunnels. 21. The surgical device of claims 17-20, wherein the actuator houses a delivery rod, wherein the delivery rod has a third diameter less than the actuator's second diameter, a third proximal end, and a third distal end; wherein the delivery rod's distal end is coupled to the one or more memory wires; wherein the delivery rod's third distal end is positioned proximal to the actuator's second distal end in the first compressed position. 22. The surgical device of claim 21 wherein the one or more memory wires are housed between the actuator's second distal end and the delivery rod's distal end in the first compressed position; wherein upon application of a second compressive or push force upon the delivery rod, the delivery rod tr